Joe:  As you probably already know, the core problem with PTSD is interpersonal relationship skills.  Your counter-post to my apology is a beautiful tribute to your high level of maturity... welcomed..but not necessary.  I over reacted.. I was looking for a fight... I abused you.  It is a cyclical thing for me to over react...under react, even isolate.  Everything is white or black, good or bad, all or nothing, win or lose, friend or foe.  Occasionally, I find the gray area and my life and I do well.  Invariably, I skid into the ditch either right or left.<br>
Instead of &quot;nothing ventured nothing gained&quot; I subcribe to &quot;nothing ventured nothing lost!&quot;  If I don't do anything... then I do nothing wrong!<br>
If you understand the physiology of the &quot;fight or flight&quot; mechanism, maybe you can appreciate that my pitutary operates wide open or fully closed.  Is this where medication comes in?  I don't take medication...I'm to stubborn to admit defeat.  I will solve my problem with reading, talking, researching, fellowship, and prayer.<br>
I only have to see the saddness in the eyes of my children to realize that &quot;I&quot; am the object of their concern.  Perhaps I can empathize with a strong young man like you who has been wounded on the perifery.<br>
I remember evacuating some wounded grunts.  They twisted and squirmed on the cargo floor in their own blood and urine.  Their Medic lay quite still in the middle of the pile... he could do no more healing for others.  I wonder if I can.<br><br>
Thanks Joe<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
